North Korea Says It's Not Coming to Talk about Rusting Down One-sidedly Without Confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that if sanctions continue, the United States' mistrust will increase, and that the country would in no way give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual general assembly of the world government that North Korea had taken "significant measures" to improve conditions over the past year, for example, they have stopped nuclear and missile tests, dismantled the nuclear test site and promise not to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we don't get anything equivalent back from the United States," he said.
"Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security, and under such circumstances it is not possible for us to unilaterally disarm first."
While Ri, a well-known North Korean, has made several complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phased" approach to the abolition of nuclear weapons, where North Korea would be paid to take gradual steps, his abdication proved significant in that he did not reject unilateral nuclear decommissioning, as Pyongyang has done.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at a first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on 12 June, when Kim promised to work for "depletion of nuclear power on the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has wanted a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions in North Korea.
"The U.S. insists on "depleting nuclear power first" and increases the pressure of sanctions to achieve its purpose by force, and they even oppose "the declaration to end peace," Ri said.
"The belief that sanctions can break us is a false hope among those who are not interested in us.
But the problem is that when the sanctions continue, our mistrust only increases."
Ri mentioned nothing about the plans for a new summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. president highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister emphasized three meetings between Kim and South Korea's leader, Moon Jae-in, over the past five months and added, "If the party to this call for nuclear weapons was South Korea, and not the United States, the Korean Peninsula debacle would not have stopped as it has now done"
Yet the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year, when he told the U.N. General Assembly that it was not possible to stop North Korean missiles against the U.S. mainland, after the evil President Trump called Kim a rocket man on suicide missions.
Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said that much work still had to be done and that sanctions had to remain in place until North Korea dismantles its nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a time frame for this, saying, "If it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should pay Pyongyang for the measures taken.
But the United States Secretary of State, Mike Pompeo, told the F.N.'s Security Council on Thursday that: "The sanctions of the Security Council must still be maintained vigorously and without fail until we get the complete, final, verified decommissioning of the nuclear weapons."
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to throttle funds for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the F.N. General Assembly and subsequently said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a new summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times already this year, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea condemns him for making "gangster-like demands."
North Korea, in a meeting with Moon this month, promised to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States took "appropriate action."
He said that Kim had told him that the "equivalent measures" he was seeking were security guarantees that Trump promised in Singapore, and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take courses in getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has helped all students get more sleep, in an effort to fight the growing macho culture of studying in caffeine rush all night long, which means that you use caffeine to stay awake all night to study.
One academic found that top university students are often careless when it comes to the very most basic - how to take care of yourself.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact sleep deprivation has on learning.
"At the end of it, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why am I being told this now, in adulthood?'
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleeping - which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, rolled out for the first time this year, explains to students what is important to how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improving their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after students received seriously poorer sleep during the week.
The hour-long course involves a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dorm room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers, and books to be told about the effect of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, as well as the importance of evening routines.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
'We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know, the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes, Prof. Czeisler added.
The culture of pride over dipping still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students means that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring you get enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student's secret weapon against stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he said - even avoiding gaining weight, since sleep deprivation puts the brain in sleep mode and makes them constantly drowsy.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, having been a student with him last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to push for a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all doctoral students to complete a similar study program before starting at the prestigious institution.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students should consider setting an alarm for when to go to bed, and also for when to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" coming from electronic screens and LED lighting, and which can re-set the internal clock altogether, leading to problems with falling asleep.
