Almanac: The Inventor of the Geiger Counter
And now a page from our "Sunday Morning" Almanac: 30 September 1882, 136 years ago today, and WE ACCOUNT ... the day when the physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, who was to become the physicist, was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the apparatus known as the Geiger counter.
As a scientific girder ever since, the Geiger counter also became a girder in pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", with the seemingly unlikely late cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What in the world is it?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, it can be used to find radioactive minerals, for example uranium.
When you put these earphones on, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms caused by the radioactivity in the minerals."
Evans: "Yes, now it's bubbling!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that asks his name lives on.
