The study by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow regular and soprano pipistrelles and also brown long-eared and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in important locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also perform mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert audio analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat calls and what species do what.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed landscape scale image of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, natural science advisor to NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat, natural homes, are most important to the bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the acquisition of meadows and how it is best to maintain forested areas for bats and other associated species.
Flag mouse populations in Scotland and across the United Kingdom have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work affecting resting places and loss of habitat/habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, such as flypaper and some chemical treatments of building materials, and also attacks by pet cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are still more useful than their eyes in catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to find faults and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly perform examinations, rest area inspections and sometimes save lives.
The organization has even created Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve on the Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says that the property is the ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threeave we have a great area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, many veteran trees and all the good habitats.
But there is much about bats that is still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive."
He stresses the importance of checking for bats before performing maintenance within properties, since it is possible that endless destruction of a single habitat could kill up to 400 female bats and juveniles, and perhaps obliterate an entire local population.
Bats are peaceful and it is illegal to kill, trouble or disturb them or destroy their resting places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to come in and help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations are endangered."
