Update on dinoflagellates: Concentration reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general reduction in the concentration of dinoflagellates in the area around Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, uneven conditions are reported for growth in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and the county around Collier – suggesting a decrease in concentration.
A growth of dinoflagellates extends over approximately 200 km on the coastline from northern Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Areas with dinoflagellates are located about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough, but compared to last week, there are fewer areas.
Dinoflagellates have been observed in Pasco.
Medium concentration has been reported in Pinellas in the last week, low to high concentration along the coast in Hillsborough, low concentration in Manatee, high concentration along the coast in Sarasota, medium concentration in Charlotte, high concentration in Lee and low concentration in Collier.
Irritation in the airways is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
Irritation in the airways was not reported in northwest Florida in the past week.
